When working with asynchronous flows handling exceptions may become a headache. Promises API provides catch method where exceptions can be caught after the call is done. While working with Backbone one is on his own. This simple solution provides a unified way for handling async exceptions.

`onTry` extends `Events.on` by wrappping the callback in try/catch what 
in the case of exception triggers `error` event in the context and calls a given error method if it's available

Examples of use:

``` javascript
// -----------
// Example 1
// -----------
// First specify what we do with exceptions
view.on("error", function(context, err){
 console.error(err);
});
// Now subscribe with exception handling
view.onTry("test-event", function(){
  // oops
    throw new Error("Test exception");
});
// Trigger async
setTimeout(function(){
 view.trigger("test-event");
}, 50);
```

``` javascript
// -----------
// Example 2
// -----------
// First specify what we do with exceptions
var globalErrorHandler = function(err) {
  console.error(err);
    // we still keep the context
    // console.dir( this );
};

// Now subscribe with exception handling
view.onTry("test-event", function(){
  // oops
    throw new Error("Test exception");
}, globalErrorHandler, view);

// Trigger async
setTimeout(function(){
 view.trigger("test-event");
}, 50);
```

