Add Haskell like function definitions using pattern matching.

In Haskell a function can be defined by pattern matching over
argument values.

``` haskell
myFunc :: Int -> Int -> String
myFunc 0 0 = "Hello"
myFunc 1 0 = "Goodbye"
```

We can define pattern matches to arbitrary arguments.

``` haskell
myFunc _ 1 = "Good Afternoon"

(myFunc 10 1) -- "Good Afternoon"
(myFunc 1 0) -- "Goodbye"
(myFunc 0 0) -- "Hello"
```

Last, we can define standard functions simply by defining functions
with non-value arguments, similar to javascript function definitions.

``` haskell
myFunc x y = "The sum is: " + (show (x+y)) 
```

Using standard function definitions in javascript, we have to use nested
if statements for each argument case. The same definitions as above are...

``` javascript
function myFunc(a, b) {
    if (b == 1){
        return "Good Afternoon"
    } 
    if (a == 0 && b == 0){
        return "Hello"
    }
    if (a == 1 && b == 0){
        return "Goodbye"
    }
    return "The sum is: " + (a+b)
}
```

_.comb allows concise pattern matching using haskell-like syntax

``` javascript
//A default function if no patterns are matched
var myFunc = _.comb(function(a, b){
    return "The sum is: " + (a+b)
})

//Cases to match on and values to return
myFunc.link(_, 1, "Good Afternoon")
myFunc.link(0, 0, "Hello")
myFunc.link(1, 0, "Goodbye")
```

The arguments to link sets patterns to match over in a first link,
first match basis. Lastly, we can pattern match on values and supply 
abstract functions to apply arguments to.

``` javascript
myFunc.link(2, _, function(a, b){
    return "Product of 2:" + (a * b)
})
```

Sum outputs with the definitions...

``` javascript
myFunc(2, 3) // 6
myFunc(10000, 1) // "Good Afternoon"
myFunc(100, 100) // "The sum is: 200"
```

A full example of definitions in javascript...

``` javascript
var myFunc = _.comb(function(a, b){
    return "The sum is: " + (a+b)
})
myFunc.link(0, 0, "Hello")
myFunc.link(1, 0, "Goodbye")
myFunc.link(_, 1, "Good Afternoon")
myFunc.link(2, _, function(a, b){
    return "Product of 2:" + (a * b)
})

myFunc(2, 3) // 6
myFunc(10000, 1) // "Good Afternoon"
myFunc(100, 100) // "The sum is: 200"
```

