## What changed?

This PR combines the concepts of state and actions into a single one, models.

A model is as if you literally merged current Hyperapp state and actions props into a single object. This change does not affect how slices work, so if you were wondering about that, now you know the answer!

How the app() function is called changed too. Instead of passing an object with named props, now you pass each prop as an argument like this:

```js
app(model, view)
```

or

```js
app(model, view, container)
```

Like before, if the view is undefined, nothing will be rendered. I found this order made the most logical sense.


## Examples
### Counter

```js
import { h, app } from "hyperapp"

const model = {
  count: 0,
  down: () => model => ({ count: model.count - 1 }),
  up: () => model => ({ count: model.count + 1 })
}

const view = model => (
  <main>
    <h1>{model.count}</h1>
    <button onclick={model.down}>-</button>
    <button onclick={model.up}>+</button>
  </main>
)

app(model, view)
```

### Clock
```jsx
import { h, app } from "hyperapp"

const angle = t => 2 * Math.PI * t / 60000

const model = {
  time: Date.now(),
  tick: () => ({
    time: Date.now()
  })
}

const view = model => (
  <svg viewBox="0 0 100 100" width="200">
    <circle cx="50" cy="50" r="45" fill="blue" />
    <line
      x1="50"
      y1="50"
      x2={50 + 40 * Math.cos(angle(model.time))}
      y2={50 + 40 * Math.sin(angle(model.time))}
      stroke="white"
    />
  </svg>
)

const model = app(model, view)

setInterval(model.tick, 1000)
```

## Why? 

### Improve the nomenclature
Stores, models, modules, slices it's all the same. Models **organize** state and actions that belong together. They are not "mixed", as that simply suggests we are conflating things that should be apart. There is no violation of separation of concerns here. 

### Simplify sharing
#### Before
```js
// ABC.js
import { B } from "./B"
import { C } from "./C"

export const state = {
  value: 0,
  B: B.state,
  C: C.state
}
export const actions = {
  add: value => state => ({ value: state.value + value }),
  B: B.actions,
  C: C.actions
}
```
#### After
```js
// ABC.js
import { B } from "./B"
import { C } from "./C"

export const model = {
  value: 0,
  add: value => state => ({ value: state.value + value }),
  B, 
  C
}
```

### Simplify slices
Because the action tree must mimic the state tree in order for slices to work, you need to duplicate the same structure twice for every namespace in the state/actions tree. You also need to keep this in mind at all times. 

### Simplify wiring setup
#### Before
```js
import  { A } from "./A"
import  { B } from "./B"
import  { C } from "./C"

app({
  state: {
    A: A.state,
    B: B.state,
    C: C.state
  },
  actions: {
    A: A.actions,
    B: B.actions,
    C: C.actions
  }
})
```

#### After
```js
import  { A } from "./A"
import  { B } from "./B"
import  { C } from "./C"

app({ A, B, C })
```

### Simplify passing props to components
#### Before

```jsx
const view = state => actions => (
  <App>
    <Feed state={state.feed} actions={actions.feed} />
    <Trend state={state.trend} actions={actions.trend} />
  </App>
)

// OR

const view = state => actions => (
  <App>
    <Feed
      model={{
        ...state.feed,
        ...actions.feed
      }}
    />
    <Trend
      model={{
        ...state.trend,
        ...actions.trend
      }}
    />
  </App>
)

// OR

import { h, app } from "hyperapp"
import { location, Route, Link } from "@hyperapp/router"
import { auth } from "./simple-auth"

const otherState = { ... }
const otherActions = { ... }

const actions = app({
  state: {
    ...otherState,
    auth: auth.state,
    location: location.state
  },
  actions: {
    ...otherActions,
    location: location.actions,
    auth: auth.actions
  },
  view: state => actions => (
    <AuthExample
      location={{
        go: actions.location.go,
        previous: state.location.previous
      }}
      login={actions.auth.login}
      userId={state.auth.userId}
      isLoggedIn={state.auth.userId !== null}
    />
  )
})

const unsubscribe = location.subscribe(actions.location)
```

#### After
```jsx
const view = model => (
  <App>
    <Feed model={model.feed} />
    <Trend model={model.trend} />
  </App>
)

//  OR

import { h, app } from "hyperapp"
import { location, Route, Link } from "@hyperapp/router"
import { auth } from "./simple-auth"

const otherModel = { ... }

const model = app(
  {
    ...otherModel,
    auth,
    location
  },
  model => (
    <AuthExample
      location={model.location}
      auth={model.auth}
      isLoggedIn={model.auth.userId !== null}
    />
  )
)

const unsubscribe = location.subscribe(model.location)
```

### Add actions dynamically

No example, but this basically means the ability to add new actions on runtime and pave the way for code splitting #439.

### Other

- Easier refactoring
- Less bugs because of typos
- This change encourages you to setup your model and view separately in a variable and then pass it to the app. This makes it easier envision how to import/export your model and view properly. ðŸŽ‰ 

## Cons

- When creating a model from [localStorage](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/localStorage), you need to deep merge it with the original model source (because the actions are removed from the object when it is persisted).

